Process called "map_float_type" takes source_lang as Integer, target_lang as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map float type to target language

    @Reasoning:
    Float spelling diverges far more than integer between languages
    (double / Float / float / Float64 / Real / Number / DECIMAL).
    Returning the language's preferred default-precision spelling
    keeps generated source idiomatic and matches each backend's
    expectation in translation/backends/*. Width-specific mappings
    (Float32 vs Float64) are handled by dedicated primitive
    mappings elsewhere, so this proc deliberately commits to one
    default-precision answer per language.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    Switch on target_lang and return the canonical float-type name.
    C-family languages get "double" (64-bit default), scripting
    languages get their dynamic numeric type, COBOL gets "COMP-2",
    and HDL/data/markup targets fall through to the source-language
    name when no native floating-point concept exists.
    @End Implementation

    If target_lang is equal to LANG_RUNA:
        Return "Float"
    End If

    Note: C-family languages
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_C:
        Return "double"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CPP:
        Return "double"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CSHARP:
        Return "double"
