Process called "map_string_type" takes source_lang as Integer, target_lang as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map string type to target language

    @Reasoning:
    String representation is the most divergent primitive between
    languages: C uses char*, C++ has std::string, Rust has &str vs
    String, JavaScript only has string, Java has String, Haskell has
    String (= [Char]), COBOL uses PIC X(255). The map_string_type
    function commits to the most idiomatic owning-string type for
    each target so generated code reads as if a native developer
    wrote it. Backends that prefer borrowed views (Rust &str) can
    introduce them post-translation during ownership inference.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    Switch on target_lang and return the canonical owning-string
    type name. Targets that lack a string primitive (assembly, raw
    binary serializations) fall through to the source-language name
    so the calling backend can lower the value as a byte sequence.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
    The mapping is purely lexical: it returns a type name. No source
    data is dereferenced, so no input validation is required here.
    The receiving backend is responsible for emitting safe string
    handling (bounds checks, escape sequences) when generating code.
    @End Security_Scope

    If target_lang is equal to LANG_RUNA:
        Return "String"
    End If

    Note: C-family languages
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_C:
        Return "char*"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CPP:
        Return "std::string"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CSHARP:
        Return "string"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_COBOL:
        Return "PIC X(255)"
    End If

