Process called "map_boolean_type" takes source_lang as Integer, target_lang as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map boolean type to target language

    @Reasoning:
    Boolean has the widest variation in spelling but the narrowest
    semantic divergence: every language can represent two values.
    Targets that lack a dedicated bool type (classic C, COBOL, x86
    assembly) get the integer encoding (typically 0/1) because that
    is what their runtime treats as truth. Modern targets (Rust,
    Swift, Kotlin) get the dedicated bool/Bool type for correct
    static typing in generated code.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
    Switch on target_lang and return the canonical boolean-type
    name. Returns "int" / "INT" / "INTEGER" for legacy targets, the
    native bool type name for modern targets, and the language's
    own truthy primitive ("Boolean", "bool", "boolean", "Bool")
    where one exists. Unsupported targets fall through to a sane
    default so HIR lowering never blocks on a missing entry.
    @End Implementation

    If target_lang is equal to LANG_RUNA:
        Return "Boolean"
    End If

    Note: C-family languages
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_C:
        Return "int"  Note: C uses int for boolean (0/1)
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CPP:
        Return "bool"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_CSHARP:
        Return "bool"
    End If
    If target_lang is equal to LANG_COBOL:
        Return "PIC 9"
    End If

